    "Html": "\r\n<p>Hi Kiran,</p>\r\n<p>If you click a button that has a Command assigned, you application should call to the CanExecute method. I created a simple sample for this, so you could download this from\r\n<a href=\"http://cid-60a74023ee1812bd.office.live.com/self.aspx/.Public/CommandingSample.zip\">\r\nhere</a> and use it as a reference.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nYou could use a breakpoint in the CanExecute method or take a look at the output window.</p>\r\n<p>Hope this helps.</p>\r\n<p>Fernando Antivero <br>\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.southworks.net/fantivero\">http://blogs.southworks.net/fantivero</a></p>\r\n",
    "PostedDate": "2010-11-08T06:56:52.823-08:00",
    "UserRole": null,
    "MarkedAsAnswerDate": null
  },
  {
    "Id": "518817",
    "ThreadId": "233784",
    "Html": "\r\n<p>Kiran,</p>\r\n<p>You just need to call</p>\r\n<p>SaveCommand.RaiseCanExecuteChanged()</p>\r\n<p>at the appropriate time - e.g. when the save command should be enabled or disabled.&nbsp; That's up to you to decide based on the state of your view model.</p>\r\n<p>Phil</p>\r\n",
    "PostedDate": "2010-11-08T08:10:15.93-08:00",
    "UserRole": null,
    "MarkedAsAnswerDate": null
  },
